nodes.title: Note: About image size
widgets_values: You can use the latent from the **EmptySD3LatentImage** to replace **VAE Encode**, so you can customize the image size.

nodes.title: Note: KSampler settings
widgets_values:
You can test and find the best setting by yourself. The following table is for reference.

| Model            | Steps | CFG |
|---------------------|---------------|---------------|
| Offical             | 50               | 4.0               
| fp8_e4m3fn             | 20                | 2.5               |
| fp8_e4m3fn + 4steps LoRA    | 4               | 1.0               |

nodes.title: Note: Raw latent version
widgets_values:
Since the **TextEncodeQwenImageEditPlus** node will scale the image to 1M pixels, you might find that the output has a pixel-shifting issue.

The **Raw latent version** is to provide the raw latent to the sampler. This is the way you can provide the raw latent as an input condition.

nodes.title: Prompt
widgets_values:
Here's the prompt structure, you can try improving on it if you like:

Make the lighting of [the subject] to match the lighting of the scene. [The subject] is [lit in a certain way] and [casts a shadow a certain way]. Maintain color, lighting and mood in the scene. Maintain the pose and details of [the subject].

Feel free to adjust as needed!

nodes.title: Crop Edge Reserve Percentage
widgets_values:
Crop Edge Reserve Percentage:
The amount to extend the character's crop by mask. The default 25% works fine. If you have props, or the character's pose nearly touches the edge of the image, perhaps consider increasing it.

nodes.title: Edge Mask Adjustments
widgets_values:
If your character or shadow are completely contained and within the edge mask, then the LayerMaskTransform, blue node, in Compositing, can be bypassed entirely. This is the default setting. When bypassed, all four edges will be feathered. Should be fine even if it remains on, although the bottom edge seam may be visible.

If your character or shadow contacts the edge of the full image, then the LayerMaskTransform must be activated. When active, the default option is is that the BOTTOM edge of the mask is not feathered. I did this because the character clipping into the bottom edge seemed like the most common form of clipping.

If your character or shadow contacts one of the side edges as well, you can further adjust manually with '1' in X Scale and either '1' (for leftward) or '-1' (for rightward) in X Move.

This setup only supports clipping one edge in each x and y direction. Anything more complicated than that and you'll need to disconnect all non-mask connections in LayerMaskTransform, calculate and enter the values manually. You can  use the expanded math node results as reference numbers to work off of.

nodes.title: Character sheet
widgets_values:
The character sheet can be generated using my Lazy Character Sheet workflow.

The character should be facing front, left, back and right, in that order.

Technically, the charaBG lora can run even if there's only one forward-facing image, or some other direction of relevance, but the character sheet works best.

Change the character in the background and pose pucture1 to a character on pictuer2. Make the lighting of the woman to match the lighting of the scene. She is a dimly backlit lavender by the moonlight and casts a clear shadow onto the ground. Maintain color, lighting and mood in the scene. Maintain the pose and details of the woman.

nodes.title: Upscaling
widgets_values:
Use your upscaler of choice.

If your character is only going to be on a small portion of your background, its recommended that you upscale your background enough so that the cropped image is at least 1 megapixel in size.

I'm using 4x remacri by default.

nodes.title: Background Image
widgets_values:
The scene to place the character in.

There should be nothing in the foreground obscuring the character.

See above for Character Dummy placement in scene.

nodes.title: Character positioning / scale / rotation
widgets_values:
Use the red "ImageBlendAdvance" node in Preprocessing to position, scale and rotate the character.

x and y percent determines the position of the character on the background. 'scale' and 'rotation' are self-explanatory.

Performance is best IF character is standing or directly in contact with the scene, with scale, position, and rotation that makes sense.

nodes.title: Color Match
widgets_values:
There is a 'Color Match' Node (Cyan) in the comp section, it tints the color of the fusion image back to match the original background image. 

It must not be bypassed, but you can adjust the strength, and, if need be, disable it by making the strength '0'.

By default I've set it to 50.

nodes.title: Character Dummy Image
widgets_values:
The Character Dummy Image should be generated using my [Lazy Character Dummy](https://civitai.com/models/2078957)

All the requirements of the Character Dummy Image can be found over there.

If you want, you can also put in grey model nude bald character image or clean line art nude bald character image and see what happens. Theoretically, it should work just fine.
